{"cursor":"45715","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"Balance of power}}\n\n{{Multiple issues |refimprove=November 2012 |cleanup=March 2010 }}\n\nThe 'separation of powers', often imprecisely used interchangeably with the\n'trias politica' principle, This latter refers specifically to the\nseparation of powers into three branches of government: legislative, executive\nand judicial. is a model for the governance of a state (or who controls\nthe state). The model was first developed in the Roman Republic as part of the\nuncodified Constitution of the Roman Republic. http://www.bible-\nhistory.com/rome/Romerome00000099.htm|Checks and Balances. http://www-\n.newworldencyclopedia.org/entry/Checks_and_balances|Checks and Balances.\nUnder this model, the state is divided into branches, each with separate and\nindependent powers and areas of responsibility so that no branch has more power\nthan the other branches. The normal division of branches is into a legislature,\nan executive, and a judiciary.\n","linknr":572,"url":"Organs_of_state","recorded":1362554117,"links":90,"instances":["united_states","law","federalism","government","government","political_meeting","government","polity"],"pdf":["http://globalasia.org/pdf/issue3/v2n2sing.pdf","http://globalasia.org/pdf/issue3/v2n2sing.pdf","http://www.florentine-society.ru/pdf/Biblical_Roots_of_Separation_of_Powers.pdf"],"categories":["Constitutional law","Philosophy of law","Separation of powers|*","Political science terms"],"headings":["Bipartite systems","Montesquieu's tripartite system","Comparison between Presidential and Parliamentary systems","Various models","See also","References","Further reading","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f4/Ambox_content.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/40px-Edit-clear.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedi